<br>
I think that introducing little changes here and there is a major portion of the problem. The main jeolousy between classes that get a tweak and those that didn't spawns the whole storm of &quot;but they got...&quot; and &quot;we need.....&quot; stuff.<br>
<br>
When they did melee balancing they put in all the damage table changes at once. Nice. Everyone got something and things were sorted out very well. Problems arise because they tweak pets a little every class that has a pet wants to see how theirs got tweaked and gets mioptic about that part of their class and why they feel they were left out.<br>
<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Europa, I have to disagree.<br>
<br>
Yes, adding one thing at a time often causes an uproar.  And the “but they got…” and “we need…” stuff makes it rather hard to judge how that change has affected the game.<br>
<br>
But that’s really the best way to do it for something as complicated as ‘caster balance’.<br>
<br>
For melee classes it really was just a matter of looking at their damage output (especially since we put off dealing with hybrid spell casting).  At that time, all we really had to do was sit down and decide what we wanted those numbers to be and then make the reality match them.  Ok, I make that sound easy, it wasn’t – it was a hell of a lot of work.<br>
<br>
We really can’t do that with casters.  When you’re talking about something that doesn’t have easily measured results, like healing or stunning or mana enhancement or whatever, then you have to take steps.  You have to make changes and watch the results, see how they affect other classes and all that.<br>
<br>
And, as Rich pointed out, even the small changes are big changes.<br>
<br>
While tossing a bunch of stuff into one patch may sound appealing, and it might appease those that get anxious when we make a change that doesn’t include them, it would be like tossing a few dozen stones into a calm pond and trying to figure out the effects of the ripples of each stone using a compass and an abacus.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
<br>
I don't like the &quot;we did some tweaking here and now we are going to do some there&quot; approach. It makes everyone who doesn't get tweaked &quot;next&quot; more upset. If you keep working one class or group of classes at a time you will only have more frustrated people wanting to know when you are going to get around to them, or come back around to them again because it wasn't enough now.<br>
<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There’s no denying that.  It happens, we’ve all seen it.  And it can make it tough to see the effects of the latest changes.<br>
<br>
But taking steps is a more, er, scientific method and makes it easier to know how each change affected the game.  We just have to trust that in the end folks will understand how and why we did it that way and that they’ll trust us in the results.  Not that we’ve done the best job of earning that trust in the past, but I’d like to think that since you’ve seen how the melee balance stuff went, and that the team pretty much nailed that, that you’d be willing to give us a little rope.  I have a ton of faith in our team and I think if you give us the time and help us take these steps that you’ll be pleased with the results.<br>
<br>
[/cheerleading off]<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
